Hi!

I just noticed that my crash log is filled with this error:

Collection was modified; enumeration operation may not execute.
at mscorlib.dll.ThrowHelper.ThrowInvalidOperationException  (0x10)
at mscorlib.dll.Enumerator.MoveNextRare  (0x13)
at mscorlib.dll.Enumerator.MoveNext  (0x4a)
at MonoGame.Framework.dll.TouchPanelState.UpdateGestures  (0x2a)
at MonoGame.Framework.dll.TouchPanelState.get_IsGestureAvailable  (0x0)
at MonoGame.Framework.dll.TouchPanel.get_IsGestureAvailable  (0x0)
at wp8_zombienstein.dll.GestureManager.Update  (0x96)

My GestureManager.Update function just caches all gestures every frame, to be later accessed

```

public static void Update (KakGameTime gt)
{
    gestureList.Clear();
    while (TouchPanel.IsGestureAvailable)
    {
        GestureSample gesture=TouchPanel.ReadGesture ();

        gesture=new GestureSample (some gesture reformatting here)

        gestureList.Add (gesture);
    }
}
```

I think this code worked previously. Unfortunately I can't make the game crash locally it's just appearing in the logs.

Any ideas?

Thanks,
Kak

Looking forward past the XNA4 API we need to start considering how multithreaded render contexts fit into the current MonoGame rendering API.

I'm thinking the core concept is a `GraphicsContext`.  Which is where we move all the core render state and commands:

```
public class GraphicsContext : IDisposable
{
   public RasterizerState RasterizerState;
   public BlendState BlendState;
   public DepthStencilState DepthStencilState;
   public Rectangle ScissorRectangle;
   public Viewport Viewport;

   public void SetRenderTarget(...);
   public void SetVertexBuffer(...);
   public void SetIndexBuffer(...);

   internal Shader VertexShader;
   internal Shader PixelShader;

   public void Clear(...);

   public void DrawPrimitives(...);
   public void DrawIndexedPrimitives(...);
   public void DrawUserPrimitives(...);        
}
```

Then we change `GraphicsDevice` to only have the per-device stuff and inherit from `GraphicsContext`...

```
    public class GraphicsDevice : GraphicsContext
    {
       public DisplayMode DisplayMode;
       public PresentationParameters PresentationParameters;
       public GraphicsProfile GraphicsProfile;

       // Creates a deferred context for building command lists in parallel.
       public GraphicsContext CreateContext();

       // Submit commands from another context to be rendered by the GPU.
       public void DrawContext(GraphicsContext context);

       public void Present();
    }
```

This way to most users the MonoGame drawing API remains pretty identical to XNA4 except for this extra `GraphicsContext` base class in there.

Next is what to do with all the `GraphicsResource` classes like `VertexBuffer`, `Texture2D`, `BlendState`, etc.  These all hold on to a `GraphicsDevice` internally for various reasons.

In the cases where they need to create resources on the "GPU" they should be using `GraphicsDevice` and this path either is or should be fixed to be thread safe.

But in the cases of actual rendering they need to know what `GraphicsContext` to apply themselves to.  Luckily most of the resources are applied to the device/context like so:

```
deviceOrContext.BlendState = myBlendState;
deviceOrContext.SetVertexBuffer(myVertexBuffer);
deviceOrContext.Textures[0] = myTexture;
```

We just need to fix the internal APIs to pass both the `GraphicsDevice` (for creating resources) and `GraphicsContext` (for state/rendering) ...  which in most cases could be the same object.

The bigger problem would be `Effect` which just does this:

```
myEffect.CurrentTechnique.Passes[0].Apply();
```

It internally sets the shaders, constant buffers, textures, samplers, and render states on to the `GraphicsDevice` it was passed at construction.  To fix this we will need a new overloaded method in `EffectPass`:

```
public void Apply()
{
   Apply(GraphicsDevice);
}

public void Apply(GraphicsContext context)
{
    context.VertextShader = _vertexShader;
    context.PixelShader = _pixelShader;
    context.RasterizerState = _rasterizerState;
    context.BlendState = _blendState;
    context.DepthStencilState = _depthStencilState;

    // etc!
}
```

This then would require anyone using the multithreaded rendering features to be sure to call `EffectPass.Apply(GraphicsContext)`.

Thoughts?

It seems that at least some operators in MonoGame are implemented with side effects and not as pure functions. For example:

```
    public static Vector2 operator /(Vector2 value1, float divider)
    {
        float factor = 1 / divider;
        value1.X *= factor;
        value1.Y *= factor;
        return value1;
    }
```

This will modify value1 itself, since X and Y are public fields and thus are mutable. This is not just a bad programming practice. This is also very different from XNA, where same operator will return a new instance for result without changing the arguments.

For example in 'a = b / c' MonoGame will change b as well, but it should not!

I don't feel entitled at all, but I am very, very surprised this is implemented like that. Could it please be changed to match XNA? I am fairly certain this is causing subtle bugs for a lot of people. The way I noticed it is when I was comparing "before" and "after" screenshots in my little physics engine. If you are using Farseer, then don't be surprised when something feels "different" after switching to MonoGame.

I hope I am being stupid and misreading / misunderstanding something, please prove me wrong...
